30) “Introduction to Personal Security” course, as it focuses on knowledge that is relevant for everyday online safety.
Throughout the module, I learned about several key areas of cybersecurity safety. This included an introduction to common social engineering techniques, such as phishing and other methods attackers use to manipulate individuals into revealing sensitive information. 
The course also covered different types of malwares, explaining how malicious software can infect systems and compromise data. Some examples are virus that attaches itself to other files in the system. Trojan horse that blends in as a legitimate software to enter systems. Ransomware, which encrypts files and systems to prevents access and some case extortion of money.
It also explored the different levels of threat associated with cyberattacks, helping to understand how attacks can vary in severity and impact. 
It also provided guidance on personal security practices, such as using strong passwords, enabling multi-factor authentication, and staying cautious when interacting with unknown links or messages.
There were topics included device hardening as well, which involves securing a device by reducing vulnerabilities and limiting potential entry points for attackers alone with basic Linux and Windows system hardening techniques.
Overall, the module provided a better understanding in personal cybersecurity and helped me understand more about online cyber security.

